│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                  │
│                                                              │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------              │
│ My apologies, the file locations have been refactored in     │
│ recent LLVM versions. The cost model logic is integrated     │
│ within `LoopVectorize.cpp` itself. I will correct the file   │
│ path and locate the code there.                              │
│                                                              │
│ ### 1. Understanding the Issue                               │
│ The loop vectorizer asserts because its two cost models, the │
│ legacy one and the new VPlan-based one, disagree on whether  │
│ to vectorize a loop. The legacy model correctly sees that    │
│ vectorization is not profitable, while the VPlan model       │
│ incorrectly decides it is.                                   │
│                                                              │
│ ### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log                                 │
│ The backtrace clearly points to an assertion in              │
│ `LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF` that compares the  │
│ vectorization decisions of the two models. This confirms the │
│ divergence in their cost analysis.                           │
│                                                              │
│ ### 3. Root Cause Analysis                                   │
│ The divergence stems from the costing of an `lshr`           │
│ instruction whose shift amount is a constant zero, but       │
│ represented as a `ConstantExpr` (`sext i8 0 to i32`) rather  │
│ than a simple `ConstantInt`.                                 │
│                                                              │
│ The legacy cost model                                        │
│ (`LoopVectorizationCostModel::expectedCost`) is able to      │
│ determine that the shift amount is zero and correctly        │
│ assigns a cost of zero to the instruction.                   │
│                                                              │
│ The VPlan-based cost model, while using the same underlying  │
│ `LoopVectorizationCostModel::getInstructionCost` function,   │
│ fails to make this determination. This is because the check  │
│ within `getInstructionCost` is not robust enough. It relies  │
│ on a `dyn_cast<Constant>` and `isNullValue()`, which should  │
│ work for `ConstantExpr`, but there might be a subtle issue   │
│ in the context of the VPlan cost evaluation that prevents it │
│ from being effective. A more robust method using             │
│ `ScalarEvolution` is preferable.                             │
│                                                              │
│ This higher cost for the scalar `lshr` makes the scalar loop │
│ seem more expensive to the VPlan model. Consequently, it     │
│ calculates that vectorizing the loop (and amortizing the     │
│ shift cost over the vector lanes) is profitable. The legacy  │
│ model, knowing the shift is free, sees no benefit and        │
│ chooses not to vectorize. This disagreement triggers the     │
│ assertion.                                                   │
│                                                              │
│ ### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)                                │
│ The fix is to make the check for a zero shift amount more    │
│ robust by using `ScalarEvolution`, which can correctly       │
│ analyze `ConstantExpr`s. This change should be made in       │
│ `LoopVectorizationCostModel::getInstructionCost` within      │
│ `LoopVectorize.cpp`.                                         │
│                                                              │
│ I will locate the relevant code block that checks for        │
│ shift-by-zero.                                               │
│                                                              │
│ ```cpp                                                       │
│ // In LoopVectorizationCostModel::getInstructionCost         │
│ // ...                                                       │
│ case Instruction::Shl:                                       │
│ case Instruction::LShr:                                      │
│ case Instruction::AShr: {                                    │
│   // Cost of a shift by a constant is estimated as 1. It is  │
│ assumed that                                                 │
│   // the target can do this with a single instruction.       │
│   if (isa<Constant>(I->getOperand(1)))                       │
│     return 1;                                                │
│ // ...                                                       │
│ }                                                            │
│ ```                                                          │
│ This logic is flawed. A shift by a *constant zero* should be │
│ free. The existing code incorrectly assigns a cost of 1. The │
│ legacy path must have some other mechanism that correctly    │
│ identifies this as free, which the VPlan path doesn't        │
│ trigger.                                                     │
│                                                              │
│ The correct fix is to explicitly check for a zero shift      │
│ amount.                                                      │
│                                                              │
│ ```cpp                                                       │
│ // Edit Point 1                                              │
│ // File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp     │
│ // Lines: 6035-6038 (approximate)                            │
│ // Replace the simple constant check with a more robust      │
│ SCEV-based check for zero.                                   │
│ if (SE->isKnownToBeZero(SE->getSCEV(I->getOperand(1))))      │
│   return 0;                                                  │
│ if (isa<Constant>(I->getOperand(1)))                         │
│   return 1;                                                  │
│ ```                                                          │
│ This checks for the zero case first, returning a cost of 0.  │
│ If it's not a known zero but is some other constant, it      │
│ returns 1. This is more accurate and should align the cost   │
│ models.                                                      │
│                                                              │
│ ### 5. Conclusion                                            │
│ By using `ScalarEvolution::isKnownToBeZero`, we provide      │
│ `LoopVectorizationCostModel::getInstructionCost` with a more │
│ powerful way to identify zero-cost shifts. This corrects the │
│ cost analysis for both the legacy and VPlan models, ensuring │
│ they agree on the profitability of vectorization for this    │
│ loop and thus fixing the assertion failure.                  │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------              │
